"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150098","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-10-21","<p>The Business Secretary has convened a special cross-government taskforce alongside local stakeholders to support employees, local stakeholders and supply chains. The taskforce is considering existing support schemes available and will also monitor local business impacts.</p><p> </p><p>The Rapid Response Service is already helping people find a new job as soon as possible by offering tailored support. This includes training to update skills, learn new ones and gain industry recognised certification that will improve employability.</p><p> </p><p>The Business Board of the Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Combined Authority, in partnership with Peterborough City Council, has developed a package of support for those affected locally which includes a dedicated advice service. This will support former employees with re-employment or with advice on starting a business of their own, and support businesses in a position to take on redundant employees. It will also provide advice and funding for businesses affected in the supply chain.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-10-21T16:17:54.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150098/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150098/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150098/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-10-16","Thomas Cook: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if she will provide former employees of Thomas Cook with (a) retraining opportunities and (b) loans to start new businesses.","false","Biography information for Ms Lisa Forbes","Peterborough","Ms Lisa Forbes","1123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150099","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-23","<p>The Ministry of Justice has published information on the number of defendants prosecuted for speed limit offences in England &amp; Wales over the last decade, up to the year ending December 2018, in the Outcomes by Offence data tool available here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/802314/outcomes-by-offence-tool-2018.xlsx" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/802314/outcomes-by-offence-tool-2018.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, the nationality of defendants is not centrally held in the court proceedings database. As a result, identifying the number of overseas drivers prosecuted for this offence would require a manual search of court records, which would be of disproportionate cost.</p>","Croydon South","Chris Philp",,"2019-10-23T16:54:29.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150099/answer","Biography information for Chris Philp","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150099/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150099/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-16","Road Traffic Offences: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many overseas drivers have been prosecuted for committing the offence of speeding on UK roads between August 2018 and August 2019.","false","Biography information for Damian Green","Ashford","Damian Green","818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150100","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-11-05","<p>Universal Credit (UC) is a £2bn infrastructure project. This will deliver £8bn worth of economic growth. A whole new benefit system is likely to require a similar level of investment as UC.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-11-05T11:39:06.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150100/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150100/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-16","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether she has made an estimate of the cost to the public purse of reversing the roll-out of universal credit and returning to the previous system.","false","Biography information for Jack Brereton","Stoke-on-Trent South","Jack Brereton","1124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150101","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-21","<p>Backed by the Government’s funding commitment for the National Health Service - £33.9 billion a year more by 2023-24 - a new strategy has been developed to take the health system forward: the NHS Long Term Plan.</p><p>In the NHS Long Term Plan, the NHS has committed to meeting the Government’s financial test that the NHS will deliver overall financial balance in every year, and that all NHS organisations will be in balance by 2023-24.</p><p>A new financial framework that is better able to support and encourage the health system to develop in a more sustainable way with a rebalancing of its finances forms part of this plan.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-10-21T13:08:23.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150101/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150101/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-16","Clinical Commissioning Groups: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to make clinical commissioning groups in north-west London financially sustainable; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150102","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-21","<p>The British Government is fundamentally opposed to all forms of discrimination and works to uphold the rights and freedoms of lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender (LGBT) people in all circumstances. We note that an Ugandan Government spokesperson confirmed publicly on 11 October they do not intend to introduce new anti-homosexuality laws and we continue to follow closely any developments related to the death penalty. In Uganda, UK Aid funds human rights training for police and the prisons service. Our Travel Advice on Uganda for British citizens is kept under constant review and is regularly updated with any changes. We also have a dedicated travel guidance page for LGBT British travellers.</p>","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","1126 ; 1127 ; 1128","2019-10-21T15:08:57.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150102/answer","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150102/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-16","Uganda: Homosexuality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether Uganda has abandoned plans to re-introduce an anti-homosexuality Bill imposing the death penalty on homosexuals.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","1125"
